ter 5: Contract Fulfilled</span><hr size=1> The trip to Freeport was always slow and tedious. Minz sat against the hull of the boat. Blind eyes staring into nothingness. The breeze was cool and comfortable after the long treck through the Butcher Block mountains. The journey had worn on him, and he leaned back relaxing for the first time in a long while. His mind teetering between wakefulness and sleep. Dreams weaving into reality and back into dreams. 'Is it right?' he though. 'Is it right that I can justify the murder of one to save another?' Sleep slowly pulled him under. 'Or is it vanity that one can think such vile actions have pure motive. The hubris of man, weighing the life of one against that of another.'<br>
<br>
He was standing now. Staring out across a vast ocean. The blue water all about him, and not another soul to be seen. He rested his hand on the gunnel. The wood was slimy and it crumbled in his grasp. The ship all about him changed. It rotted and crumbled before his very eyes. Foul stinking planks held together by rusted nails and broken pegs.<br>
<br>
&quot;Like a dead and decaying ship,&quot; a voice said aloud. &quot;Driven by the white breezes of the north.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Does the sweet breeze that pushes this ship make its journey beautiful and righteous?&quot; he asked the voice. &quot;Or does the simple black nature of the vessel make it to dark to for any purpose to make right?&quot;<br>
<br>
Minz looked to the heavens for an answer, but all he saw where the ships masts, tipped poison dragging an infected, seeping gash across the sky. The ship's sails unfurled. A death shrouds for its one passenger.<br>
<br>
The bell tolled out the hours.<br>
<br>
Charon was at the helm. His tattered cassock hanging low over his dead eyes.<br>
<br>
A pile of gold coins sat at his feet.<br>
<br>
&quot;Is the journey vile no matter what wind drives it?&quot; He asked the silent helmsman. Charon motioned to the cabin. His hand sweeping back in a sickeningly slow gesture.<br>
<br>
Minz ventured into the depths of the ship. Deeper and deeper he marched. The stairs descended far below the waterline of the ship's hull. The deeper he went, the more solid the timbers became. &quot;And what's this?&quot; He shouted. His voice echoed up the long stairwell. &quot;The wood at the ships center is solid? Is it hard because it is undecayed? Or is it worse than the rest? Incorruptible because it is already corrupted?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Where can such a deathly ferry take one but down to the bottom of the ocean.&quot; The voice answered. &quot;But to the foulest depths where the water's pressure crushes out all that is unnecessary. Leaving the essential core.<br>
<br>
&quot;The heart.<br>
<br>
&quot;The pebble that rests at the center each of us.&quot;<br>
<br>
Minz held the amulet in his hand. The hard black stone embedded within it glimmered in the light.<br>
<br>
&quot;Where will I go from here?&quot; he asked.<br>
<br>
An ocean appeared before him. Its waters were dark and turbulent.<br>
<br>
Across the distance he saw them, his friends. He reached out, leaning over the water, needing them now more than ever. Yet with each breath of wind into the sails, they sunk further beneath the horizon.<br>
<br>
&quot;How will I reach across the vast sea that I have put between myself and those I care for?&quot; He asked. &quot;The deed I have pledged to complete for their sake sends me further and further away. Though they would abhor it, it must be done.&quot;<br>
<br>
The brackish waters turned crimson. A red tide pushing the ship father and father around the curve of the earth. Until the visage of those loved was gone.<br>
<br>
'All I can see is not that which I had faced,' he mused ironically. 'Not the clean and lovely ones called friends, but the fetid enemy that I run from. That I am becoming.'<br>
<br>
A mast stabbed up over the horizon. Another black ship making passage across this empty sea. A lone passenger stared across the gunnel at Minz. His hollow eyes sunken deep into the recesses of his face. Blue skin taught with hatred and deceit.<br>
<br>
'The reflection at the edge of the earth is me,' he thought, recognizing the form as himself. 'And it is a black black thing I do.'<br>
<br>
The sound of the harbor bell brought him out of his slumber. &quot;All ashore that's goin ashore,&quot; the first mate called out. Minz rose from his spot. Stretching sore muscles that ached from being prone in one position for too long. He rested his hand on the gunnel of the ship. Pausing a moment to feel its solidity. And then walked toward the gangway, feeling his way to the dock, by holding his hand on the gunnel as he walked, and then the rope of the gangway as he crossed onto the docks of Freeport.<br>
<br>
One step closer to his mark.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
The land slipped by in blurred images. Some on the most beautiful scenery in the world, faded into the background. Even the Karanas slipped by unnoticed. The land he knew so well, places where he used to play, the ol' swimmin hole, the family's farm, not even an after thought. He was preparing for a job. Nothing else mattered.<br>
<br>
Much of the trip he was able to make in Tier Dal form. Though he had become quite proficient at traveling blind, sight speeded up the trip immensely. Throughout the journey he reviewed all he knew of his target: Kassy Lightborn.<br>
<br>
'Wood elf by birth. Now some how a Tier Dal.' He chuckled ruefully at the irony. 'She was perhaps one of the few people in the world who could understand what he was going through. And he was going to kill her . . . An enchantress by art. . . Smart and cunning . . . but I should be able to get close enough. Lives in Qeynos alone. . . Accepted by the community. . . Well like by all accounts. . . She will not suspect me so long as I am a half elf. . . ' For most jobs he would spend a day or two watching his mark, getting to know them. But he knew this one very well already.<br>
<br>
She was a friend to the Dragons and a friend to him.<br>
<br>
But that was all over now.<br>
<br>
He held her face in his mind for a moment, studying the features. Following the lines of her neck in his mind's eye. It was thin, almost frail. He envisioned his blade sliding across her throat, the skin peeling open as the keen edge passed over her blue skin, noting the three, or four actually, important vessels to be cut: the carotid arteries, the trachea and jugular vein.<br>
<br>
If one successfully opened all of these vessels the likelihood of survival was close to nil. Within 5 minutes, over half of the body's blood drained out, air ceases being delivered to the brain, and the lungs fill with enough blood to drown the victim. Additionally, slitting the throat lessened the likelihood of the victim crying out. This could also be achieved by plunging a blade between the fifth and sixth ribs and into the right lung. But the likelihood of a quick death was better with the throat. The downside to this attack was that the poison is often not absorbed sufficiently. A direct stab to the heart or lungs was much more efficient in this regard.<br>
<br>
Nonetheless, a slit thought was the way to do it. One second . . . two tops. That was all it took. And her life would be ended. Ohh she wouldn't die that quickly, but her life would be done. He thought back to his teacher, Cerawyn, and to their practice sessions late at night in Freeport. &quot;Not like that boy!&quot; he'd say. Chastising Minz for making a sweeping curved slice across some whore's throat. &quot;Don't get all artsy fartsy on me, makin some smiley face on their neck! Like this!&quot; he would grab the now dead body by the hair, lifting her dead form and slit her throat again. &quot;One. Two. Straight down, pivot and straight up. That's all.&quot;<br>
<br>
Later, Cer had taught him about the anatomy of the body; where the critical veins and arteries were and how their locations varied slightly depending on the race. It was a hell of a lot more book learning that he had ever anticipated.<br>
<br>
The first guard tower of Qeynos could be seen in the distance. He stopped well out of sight, most Tier Dal were not welcome here. Opening his shirt, he ran his fingers over the living amulet. It was natural now, like it was a part of him. Despite the constant wound it created, he drew comfort and strength from it. It was hard to describe, there was little middle ground any more. It was either right or wrong. Friend or enemy.<br>
<br>
He slipped a finger underneath the spider. It wriggled in protest, but didn't resist as it had earlier. They were coming to know one another. He pulled gently, and the amulet came free. Its needle like legs slipping out of their sanguine moorings. The world went black. Skin stretched and tingled. A vague shifting in his belly and it was done. He could have kept walking throughout the process if he wanted too. Not that the change had become any less painful, he had simply become used to it. The wound on his chest had become a permanent gash. Constantly seeping blood no matter what body he was in. Blood now covered the front third of his shirt. But the black scaled armor he wore covered most of the gore.<br>
<br>
The path to the city was paved with rough flagstones. This made it easy to follow, but hard to walk. He was constantly tripping on the rough and uneven joints of the stones. Several times he ended up flat on his face. But soon enough he was at the gates of the city. Qeynos was just as he remembered it, except that he couldn't see it. Tubal Weaver haggled over prices with his customers. The guards extorted platinum wherever they could. The smells of the merchant stalls wafted through the city.<br>
<br>
His first stop was the Crow tavern, and the rogue's guild hidden within. Minz laughed to himself as he rounded the corner to the bar. As a child, he'd boasted that he could find his way through Qeynos blind. Today he was proving himself right, deftly walking through the wide avenues and tight alleys, never missing a step. Using his childhood memories and the constant echoes of his harpoon rapping the ground.<br>
<br>
It was customary for a rogue on a job to pay a &quot;courtesy call&quot; on the rogue guildmaster when on contract in a foreign town. The mark's name and the assassin were recorded, and clearance is given. Not that contracts weren't completed without the guild's blessing. Happened all the time. But the courtesy call ensured the assassin was up to date on local conditions and prevented two rogues from going after the same mark. The guild would also provided assistance in exiting the city and independent confirmation that the job was completed.<br>
<br>
Guildmaster Hanns Kreighor questioned him in his usual direct manner. &quot;Name o' the mark?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Kassy Lightborn.&quot; Minz replied. The faint scratch of a quill could be heard.<br>
<br>
&quot;Contractor?&quot;Hanns said flatly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Undisclosed.&quot; was his reply. More scribbling.<br>
<br>
&quot;Contracted?&quot; Hanns said.<br>
<br>
&quot;Minz Elandril.&quot;<br>
<br>
A silent pause, the tiny clink of a quill dipped into an inkbottle followed by more scribbling. &quot;Right. You're all set.&quot; Hanns said, rolling the blotter across the page and closing the book with a thwump. &quot;Luck in the shadows.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Luck in the shadows.&quot; Minz responded to the familiar rogue salutation.<br>
<br>
He left the guild, and headed back to the bar above. The echoing drip of the aqueducts could be heard in the background. He rounded the corner and walked up the stairs. Slipping through the illusionary wall. A tingle on his skin told him that he was passing through the magic. Generally, rogues shunned magic, and Hanns' near phobia for it was common knowledge among the rogue community. But he had obviously made a compromise here.<br>
<br>
Kassy lived on the residential west side of town. 'No sense in hiding. Hell, she'll probably invite me in!&quot; Minz smiled crookedly to himself as he started off toward her house. The west side of Qeynos was a quiet and intimate place. Avenues narrow to slim paths. Scowling business like faces give way to friendly glances. Pleasantries were commonly exchanged between strangers and even the stiff, tight posture of the guards seemed to soften.<br>
<br>
The smell of baking bread wafted through the air. Bringing thoughts of home bubbling to the surface of Minz's mind. It was a clear spring day he remembered. Puffy clouds drifted by slowly. He and his brother were playing in the field next to the house. Climbing the large tree that dominated the otherwise open space.<br>
<br>
Minz was laughing at his brother, who hung upside down, his arms dangling, face becoming bright red as the blood rushed to his head.<br>
<br>
Mom was cooking dinner: beef stew with carrots and potatoes and fresh bread to mop up every last bit from the bowl. 'Yum!' They'd already been tossed out of the kitchen once for pestering mom, and were now fighting the siren's call of her cooking again. He smiled<br>
<br>
The rock jutted out of the flagstone walk, making a rough 2-inch ledge in the otherwise smooth surface of the path. It was perfectly visible, and easily avoidable. But vision was a luxury for Minz now. And the price of that luxury was an almost universal hatred by all those who walked the earth.<br>
<br>
His toes hit the rock hard, sending the rogue stumbling forward, letting go of his harpoon and thrusting his arms out in an attempt to catch hold of something, anything to avoid another painful fall. Large hands grasped him, slipping under his arms, effortlessly bringing his tumble to an end. Minz's hands instinctively locked onto the extended thick forearms of the stranger.<br>
<br>
&quot;Easy boy,&quot; his savior said the deep rumbling voice of a Northman. Minz stood there for a moment, catching his breath and trying to regain his barings. &quot;Ya alright?&quot; He asked as he righted Minz.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yea, I'm fine,&quot; he said, releasing his clamped fingers from the barbarian's arms. The hulking man had the pungent smell of a barbarian too. &quot;Thanks,&quot; he said, giving his best self-effacing grin.<br>
<br>
The Northman was still a moment, gauging Minz. The quiet sounds of the neighborhood filtered back into Minz's ears. 'Probably noticing I'm blind,' Minz thought. He heard the big man move a bit, and the clank of hardened wood on stone.<br>
<br>
&quot;Here ya be,&quot; the Northman said. Minz reached out and felt the shaft of his harpoon placed in his hand.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thanks again,&quot; Minz said as a Qeynos guard marched by.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do ya know where you're headin friend?&quot; The barbarian asked in a amicable voice. &quot;Perhaps I can help ya find it?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm alright,&quot; Minz replied smiling. &quot;It's just up the lane a bit. Thank you again. Safe travels to you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And to you friend,&quot; the barbarian replied.<br>
<br>
Minz rapped his harpoon on the stone, listening to the echoes carefully as he started on his way.<br>
<br>
Kassy's flat actually was just a bit down the lane, but Minz purposefully walked right by it, turning down the next alley. Pressing his back to the wall. Making damn sure his barbarian friend had plenty of time to leave the vicinity.<br>
<br>
Minz waited about 15 or 20 minutes, listening for a pause in the traffic. Once the avenue was empty, he emerged from the alley. Rapping his harpoon on the stone and taking several quick steps to Kassy's door. He steeled himself inwardly, but lightly touched the feelings of friendship and affection he felt for her. She had to be at ease with him. To face her when she was readied for battle was suicide. To succeed, Minz had to strike when her guard was down.<br>
<br>
He closed his eyes unconsciously, sending the assassin in him to a dark corner in his mind. He knocked on the door.<br>
<br>
A moment passed.<br>
<br>
The click of the latch turning fell lightly on his ear.<br>
<br>
He opened his eyes and smiled as best as he cold. He was Minz Elandril, here visiting a dear friend. There was an uncomfortable pause. This was not the greeting he expected, and it sent butterflies into his stomach. &quot;Kassy?... I... Can I come in?&quot; She muttered &quot;yes&quot;, and he stepped through the door, bumping into something and almost ending up flat on his face.<br>
<br>
She seemed to grasp the his predicament, yet remainescilent, leadin him into her flat. Minz thumped his harpoon. The room they were in was wide. It likely took up the entire flat. The echoes were softened some what, and the air had the bitter green smell of a Faydwer forest. They walked slowly around the room, stopping some fifteen steps from the door. &quot;Sit here. There is a chair is right behind you,&quot; she said. Minz felt a gentle tug on his harpoon, and reluctantly let it be taken from his hand as he sat down. The chair was wide and comfortable, covered in an earthy woven fabric Minz recognized as being native to Faydwer.<br>
<br>
&quot;Blind? By the gods!&quot; She cried as Minz finally said it out loud. &quot;How. . . ? When?&quot; She clasped his shoulders, pulling him into a tight hug. &quot;Oh Minz. . . can it . . . have the healers seen you? I have friends who can. . .&quot; He wrapped his arms around her. Somewhat taken aback by her affection but touched nonetheless. Squeezing her slender frame once and pushing her away.<br>
<br>
&quot;Kassy,&quot; he said with a sigh. &quot;I have seen many who have tried. I am blind.&quot; Finality hung in his voice. She let a hand slip from his shoulder, sliding down his arm, clasping soft delicate fingers over his hand. Clenching his jaw, he pushed down a pang of guilt as it welled up in his throat.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll be right back,&quot; she said. He heard Kassy's light steps pad away, a door swung open on well oiled hinges, the soft pop of a bottle being uncorked. She had such light steps that Minz, even paying close attention, had trouble hearing her return. When her fingers touched his hand, raising it to press a glass into it, it sent a chill shock through his body. His surprise must have been visible, because she immediately began to gush apologies. &quot;Oh Minz! I am so sorry. I didn't mean to sneak up on you. I just. . .&quot;<br>
<br>
He cut her off mid sentence. &quot;Hush. It's ok. You're fine.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ohhhh Minz. I just . . . just can't believe it,&quot; she said. &quot;Tell me what happened. How did you lose your sight? When? Who have you seen to remedy it and what have they tried to?&quot;<br>
<br>
Minz retold the story, of hunting with Jez in Oasis and becoming lost in the desert. How he awoke in the care of Sylavn and Jing, unable to see a thing. Of his travels to Odus and the surgery he under went, leaving out the rather distasteful details of course. Of reuniting with the Dragons and Tryllium's diagnosis.<br>
<br>
&quot;Minz! There has to be some thing we can do,&quot; she said. &quot;Let me call on my friend. She is wise in the ways of healing. One of the wisest in the land. . .&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Kassy!&quot; He said. &quot; Please, let it be.&quot;<br>
<br>
She sighed heavily. &quot; Can I get you something? Somthing to eat perhaps? You look exhausted.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;More than you know, Kass. More than you know. Now what was th. . .&quot;<br>
<br>
But it was Kassy's turn to interrupt him. &quot;Right!&quot; she said. &quot;It's into bed with you.&quot; Her small hands encircled his wrist. &quot;News can wait.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But . . . But. . .&quot; he sputtered.<br>
<br>
&quot;No buts mister, now come on.&quot; she said, hauling him toward the back of the house.<br>
<br>
&quot;But Kass. . . &quot; He protested. &quot;I mean its not like I mind you dragging me into your bedroom. . .&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dream on lover,&quot; she replied as she pushed him backward on to the bed.<br>
<br>
Minz spread his arms wide, a wry grin on his face. Kassy tugged at his boots, wrenching them off his feet. &quot;Will you still respect me in the morning?&quot; He said, barely able to contain his laughter. Kassy groaned as she headed for the door. &quot;Be gentle with me,&quot; he said, giggling merrily, as the door slammed shut.<br>
<br>
The giggling dribbled out of him. Ending softly, like the last drop of a rain seeping into the earth. The room was silent. Curtains rustled softly in the afternoon breeze. The sounds of the city floated in and Kassy's soft steps were barely audible in the background.<br>
<br>
He waited for a good while to pass, slowly letting go of that part of him that held Kassy dear. Bit by bit he chipped away at the feelings, consciously dismissing each pang of guilt and remorse as it surfaced. 'What the Brell?' he asked himself. 'What are you doing here?' 'What has to be done,' came the cold retort in a voice not quite his own. 'But Kassy is a friend?' He silently pleaded. 'Its Kassy or Silverstarr. One of them will die. Its up to you to decide.'<br>
<br>
Minz sighed heavily. It had been so easy once. So wonderful to be who he was: a thief and a young member of a respected guild. But now. . . Now he was the leader of that guild, responsible for the well being of its members. And one of them was in mortal danger now. Silverstarr, one of the youngest members of his guild, was held hostage. And the price of her freedom was the death of Kassy Lightborn. &quot;So be it,&quot; he said aloud. He reached into his pocket, wrapping his hand around the now familiar amulet, running his fingers over the spindly legs and smooth stone embedded in its abdomin. With his free hand, the thief pulled his shirt open at the collar bringing his other hand up and resting the spider amulet on the seeping wound in his chest. As soon as it touched his skin, it came to life, wriggling itself into his flesh.<br>
<br>
The changes washed over him. Light flooded into his eyes, and he was drow. Some how the reservations he had earlier seemed trivial. He was here to do a job. That was all that was important. The room was small. Light earthy colored walls. Lush green plants decorated the room. The door was narrower than normal. He crept to the door, leaving his shoes behind for the added silence of bare feet, inspecting the hardware. Its brass hinges showed a bit of wear, potentially creaky. Minz retrieved an oilcloth from a pocket and rubbed it over the hinges.<br>
<br>
The door opened silently. A soft breath of air puffed through the door. Minz froze. Kassy was no fool. She was experienced in battle. Though her skills were of a different nature, her senses were keen. The slightest mistake could tip her off, spelling certain death for him.<br>
<br>
The room was rectangular, yet the arrangement of plants and furniture gave it the appearance of being an oval. Clearly reminiscent of the homes of the wood elves of Kelethin. Kassy sat at a desk facing one of the longer the wall. The door he came out of was at the far end of the oval. He could see her profile clearly, her eyes intently studying a small book. Random papers and other books were strewn about the desk. A stark contrast to the clean orderly appearance of the rest of the room.<br>
<br>
Minz silently crept around her, his eyes locked on her. She muttered quietly as she read, scribbling on a notes long sheaf of paper. Occasionally reaching to her necklace, clasping a silver charm in her hand. He took his steps sideways, always keeping Kassy directly in front of him.<br>
<br>
Three more steps and he would be in position.<br>
<br>
Two steps. He was directly behind her. He drew his dagger from its sheath.<br>
<br>
One step. The scent of the dracnid poison filled his nostrils.<br>
<br>
He was behind her, reaching out to grab her head, dagger held with its blade ready to slice into her blue skin.<br>
<br>
Her head shot up.<br>
<br>
She spun with a quickness he'd not expected, shooting to her feet, gasping at his sight. Their eyes locked. Minz felt his heart jump into his throat. Not for fear, though fear clenched his gut, but in guilt. This wasn't some anonymus mark. This was Kassy.<br>
<br>
His hand shot out like an arrow seeking its target. Piercing her chest, sinking deeply into her heart.<br>
<br>
Her mouth dropped open in a gasp. Eyes wide with horror. Minz grinned at her, pushing her down on the desk with his dagger, arching her back and pinning her to the sold wood of her desk. Blood spurted over his hand in weak pulses. He leaned over her, still pressing her to the desk with his blade. His heart pounded in his chest. Sickening fear, guilt and exhilaration washed over him, yet some how compelled to revel in it. Brushing his lips to her, wanting to breathe in her last breath. Her eyes were wide with agony, and he stared into them for what seemed an eternity. Slowly, her body slid to the floor. Minz cradled her with his free arm, lowering her gently to the well worn planks of her home. Kassy's eyelids began to flutter. Minz twisted the blade hard, and they shot back open, she grasped his chest, slender fingers clenching what ever they could find.<br>
<br>
He jerked the blade out of her chest. She flinched, jerking her arms to her chest and crying out softly. There was a tugging, ripping sensation in his chest, but he ignored it, caught up in the ecstasy of Kassy's death. And then everything went black.<br>
