There was a quiet knock at the door. Kassy cursed under her breath as she rose from her desk, laying aside both the small leather-bound book she was reading and her mithril-tipped quill. She had informed her numerous friends, as well as the boys who normally delivered her groceries, that she was going to be busy with delicate arcane research and was not to be disturbed. Only Xareth's messenger, who came every second day to carry away her translations of the book's contents, had seen the interior of the house within the past week. Yet there was knocking at her door.<br>
<br>
The irritated look vanished from the elf's face as she opened the door to find Minz Elandril on her front stoop. It was not only the fact that it was Minz that banished her irritation, however, but that she sensed there was something terribly wrong but couldnt put her finger on it. The rogue was ashen and looked on the verge of trembling. His atire was travel worn, nearly unheard of as the half-elf was very nearly a perfectionest. He seemed to be looking past her and she looked him in the face, trying to discover why he avoided her gaze. Then, looking into his eyes, she realized that the half-elf's were pale green when they should have been deepest brown!<br>
<br>
&quot;Kassy... I... Can I come in?&quot; He sounded unsure of himself, nervus. The enchantress mumbled a confused yes and stepped aside to allow him to enter her home. As Minz passed her he stumbled over a potted fern in the entryway. The plant was nearly three feet tall and in plain sight. Kassy gasped; Minz was blind. The next few moments were hectic. Kassy leading the sightless rogue to the over-stuffed chair in the corner of her front room, fretting over him, asking question after question, assuring him that she would do whatever was in his power to help him regain his sight, and not leaving his side. This only upset Minz all the more. He cringed away from her touch as though it burned him, finally silencing the young Tier'Dal with a harsh look from his sightless green orbs. After several moments of polite pleasentries Kassy commented on the bags beneath her friend's eyes.<br>
<br>
&quot;You look exhausted, Minz,&quot; she said. With a few muttered protests and smartassed comments from the rogue she led him to the smaller of the two bedrooms in the house and left him there to rest, returning to her translations.<br>
<br>
The elf's eyes narrowed, again reading over the same line for at least the ninth time. She knew she had translated it properly, but it made no sense. Again she read the words aloud to herself, &quot; 'Here broken and here to be rebound, the strife's end must be sought before the joining of two, lest three be the outcome.' Xareth and Silverstarr are the two... How could three be the outcome?&quot; She shook her head, causing the platinum chain around her neck to move, swinging her emblem of Tunare slightly.<br>
<br>
She brought her hand to the charm to stop it's movement, inhaling sharply as her fingers touched the runed silver leaf. It was warm. Kassy thought she heard a slight scuff behind her and turned, but nothing was out of place. Shrugging off her sudden uneasiness as nothing more than a symptom of stress, she returned her eyes and thoughts to the book that lay open on her desk. Staring again at the sentence that troubled her she tried to force her mind to clear of all but the flowing text.<br>
With every minute that passed, though, she became more uneasy. Something wasnt right and she didnt know what. Putting her hand to the emblem of her goddess again a shiver of fear swept over her. The metal was pulsing, the movement becoming quicker with every beat. Terrified, Kassy stood and whirled around...<br>
<br>
The blade slid into the soft ebony skin of the enchantress' chest as she turned, blood wetting the hands of her attacker, red on blue-black. The Tier'Dal asassin looked down at her with cold green eyes as she brought a hand to her chest, trying hopelessly to seal the mortal wound. She tried in vain to stay on her feet, falling to the ground as the strength left her knees, and grabbing desperately at her attacker for support.<br>
<br>
Her weakening hand closed around an amulet that clung to the assasin's chest, but it was not enough to keep her upright. The was a tearing sensation and she fell to her back on the floor, the Tier'Dal's amulet still in her hand. As the charm came free of her attacker a change swept imeadiatly. His skin paled and his hair darkened. His ears lost their gracefully long points, becoming almost round, only slightly pointed. Only his cold green eyes remained the same. But now they were sightless. Kassy shook her head in denial, the movement hardly noticable and completely unseen by the blood-drenched half-elf who stood before her. The pain of her wound vanished in that moment, consumed by the pain of betrayal.<br>
<br>
Unable to breath all she could do was mouth the question, &quot;Minz...? Why...?&quot; Then the rogue she had called friend faded from her sight as her once sparkling saphire eyes dimmed. The world went black, and Kassy Lightborn saw no more.<br>
