<br>
He ignored that burning itch as best he could and gazed out across the savanna.  The messenger would be arriving soon.<br>
<br>
The messenger arrived in due time, a young half elf. Xareth almst chuckled at the thought; the boy looked older then he did, and was far older in reality. Normally the Teir'Dal did not care to employ messengers that were not loyal to his cause, but this one could get in and out of Qeynos safely, and was paid well enough to obey. Xareth made sure he obeyed too, and reminded him occasionally of what happened to those who crossed his people. It was enough.<br>
<br>
Xareth stood and waited for the lad to approach.  &quot;Well?&quot;<br>
<br>
The sandy brown head bowed.  &quot;S-she would not answer the door, m'lord.  But her house was lit.&quot; The boy edged back a pace at the Dark Elf's growl.  &quot;But I went to see what was wrong!&quot; he added hurriedly. &quot;I went around to the back and look into her window.  She was lying on the floor in a pool of blood, and parchment was scattered everywhere.&quot; The boy dared a glance at Xareth.<br>
<br>
The warrior ignored the curiousity.  Kassy, dead? &quot;Did you see how she was slain?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye, m'lord.  She's been stabbed in the chest.&quot; <br>
<br>
He pondered the information a moment. The heathen Teir'Dal was liked by the folk of the light cities, that much he knew. And only one person he knew had been contracted to slay her. <br>
<br>
He pulled out a small bag of gold and handed it to the boy. &quot;Take this and return to me with any parchments you find that she had been working on.  Do not miss any of them. And find a small black diary that should be with them.  I want to see these items by sundown tomorrow.  Understood?&quot; The boy nodded. &quot;Go, you haven't any time to waste.&quot;<br>
<br>
He watched the half elf bound away for Qeynos, brown hair flying. Kassy, slain. He knew good and well who'd taken her life.  No one else would have dared upon one who had so many powerful friends. Xareth was a little uneasy at the repercussions, but there was nothing to be done now.  His sending Minz to do the job had been excecuted at last, but the rogue's timing was bad indeed. he'd sent a messenger out to find Minz when Kassy had agreed to translate the book, to have him cry off the hunt until the translation was complete.<br>
<br>
That messenger had never returned. <br>
<br>
Well, what was done was done. The best he could do now was to get what had been translated and put it to use. With any luck at all, there would be something of worth in the translation.  Still, he couldn't help but be angry.  The rogue had probably timed the kill for the purpose, damn him.  He would have to do something about it.<br>
<br>
Xareth made his way back to his post, seething with anger and pointedly ignoring the constant itch of the light skin.<br>
