Munz had stopped trying to refuse drink from the revelers some hours ago, and was by sunset quite drunk. <br>
<br>
All around him, the mountains of the Frozen Wastes vaulted skyward like frozen fingers trying to warm themselves against the fading light of the setting sun. Brightly colored fur-trimmed costumes whirled by, in time to the jig Munz played and sang. The sounds and smells of laughter and feasting ebbed and flowed in a ceaseless tide. <br>
<br>
Munz set his lute aside and leaned heavily against a great stone table, gathering himself for another set. <br>
<br>
Men and women of the North were celebrating Whitsunday, the end of the shortest day of the year. Each day from here on out would grow longer and longer until Midsummer, and then the days would fade earlier and earlier, and the sun would resume an ever-more-southerly course in it's daily sojourn accross the steel blue sky. <br>
<br>
It was a cause of great joy, for the Feast marked the end of long, cold nights on the tundra, and the return of light, warmth, and hopes for a good harvest on the windswept plains to the south. Whitsunday Feast was also the time for the Northern women to chose their mate, and to become with child so that they might give birth on the warm grass in the full of the summer. <br>
<br>
Munz had wandered past the low stone cottages only the day before. He had been travelling, running, hiding from someone or something, or himself. He chose his path at random, content to lay his fate in the hands of whatever gods might trouble themselves to look after it. He had stopped to ask for a crust or a coin, and was told he could have his fill of both the next night, if he would only play. <br>
<br>
A young barbarian girl, solid, blonde and buxom - twelve years Munz's junior yet towering above him - whirled up to him. She thrust another goblet of braggot into his left hand, and a huge, naked breast in his right. She stood quite close, smiling down on him. She was herself clearly quite drunk, breathing heavily with the exertion of the dance. Her breast heaved in his hand, and her hot breath was scented by cherry wine. <br>
<br>
&quot;Shall I choose you, little Bard?&quot; Her girlfriends giggled and tittered from a safe distance, as a few Barbarian men seemed to notice the play. They glowered at Munz from behind haunches of roasted meat. <br>
<br>
Munz hefted her breast once or twice thoughtfully, as though carefully considering her offer. <br>
<br>
&quot;If only you would, but I fear my Flute is too small for your liking.&quot; <br>
<br>
The girl laughed and skipped off to rejoin her friends. The men who had been watching howled in laughter and returned their attention to the great platters of fruit and pastry before them. <br>
<br>
Munz smiled crookedly, his head still swimming in a drunken stupor. He remembered the braggot in his left hand, and drank greedily. He gazed after the girl with wet, bloodshot eyes and imagined for a moment what it might be like to drown himself in that great sea of gorgeous flesh. <br>
<br>
Suddenly, a cloud swept accross his vision. He could not see, and the sounds of the feast were suddenly muffled and distant, as though someone had dropped a woolsack over his head. <br>
<br>
He staggered a moment and clutched at his head. The goblet he had been holding clanged on the stones as he dropped it, but even that seemed muffled. He staggered away from the table with his head in his hands, and he heard distant laughter as the men watched what they must have thought was some new jest. Munz dropped to his knees. <br>
<br>
The dark mist before his eyes seemed to part. He seemed to be in some other dark place altogether. Suddenly, he could smell brine and dark rot. He realized that there were walls of timber to either side, stretching forward into darkness. He seemed to hover high above a plank floor. <br>
<br>
He watched as a figure stumbled into view, far below him. He could not make out the features of the man below, but as the mists swirled in and out of his vision, the skin on the figure seemed to be blue, like that of a T'ier Dal, but then turned pale like his own. The figure looked up, perhaps in an effort to ascertain the location for himself. <br>
<br>
Munz looked down upon his own visage. <br>
<br>
The mists swirled black and heavy, blotting out the vision - but soon a set of clear sapphire eyes materialized before him, quite close. They were wide with surprise or fear - or both. In a few moments, they too faded into the mist of his vision. <br>
<br>
Munz did not feel his head smack hard on the stones as he fell forward from his knees and lay prone on the cold ground. He did not hear the men howl with laughter at this latest antic of the stange Bard. <br>
<br>
He slept as the Dance whirled on about him. He slept as the waning orb of the sun slipped into the waiting grasp of the mountains. He slept as the stars wheeled and flashed above him in a heavenly Dance of their own.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uxarethsthanos.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xareth S thanos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#CC9900>(8/9/01 1:37:06 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Contract Fulfilled</span><hr size=1> (ooc - posting this for Merecraft)<br>
