The wind was blowing a gale up here in the peaks of the Skyfire Mountains. After a week of hunting the minions of Scale here, Merecraft Oakenheart had become used to the cold, biting wind, and it was with a resigned shrug that the half-elf pulled the cloak of mammoth fur closer around his shoulders and settled down to sleep. The druid's fire had burned low, emitting only a soft glow in the small depression amongst the rocks where he had settled for the night. The day had been a successful one and he had managed to track down another of the lost prayers of Tunare that the minions had stolen from her temples. Still, as he relaxed and made his plans for the morrow one image kept forcing its way into his mind, that of a dark face with large luminous eyes that drew his soul out into the Light. <br>
<br>
It was a face that had become more dear to him than all else, the face that had saved his soul from the darkness that had threatened to engulf it when he had left the Knight Templar under a cloud of suspiscion and hurt. Over the past few weeks he had grown closer to Kassy Lightborn than he had ever been to any other. He had fallen deeply in love with the young Teir Dal, a fact that still astonished him at times. What astonished him even more was that her feelings for him had grown just as strong. He smiled to himself as he thought back to the days they had spent on the islands of the Ocean of Tears, the two of them alone for days on end, finding comfort and a growing bond in each others company. After all that had happened, the betrayal of his brother, the murder of Nostramis, the loss of his mother, and the curse of Carinus, the half-elf felt happier than he had in years. <br>
<br>
Kassy and Merecraft had only been seperated for a week, but it already felt like a lifetime. She had gone back home to Qeynos on an urgent matter which required some days of research. The druid hadn't enquired too deeply, he knew that Kassy would tell him when she was ready, but he knew her well enough to know that her journey was very important. Still, this time next week they would be together again, and Merecraft's heart soared at the thought of seeing the young enchantress once more. <br>
<br>
Still smiling to himself in the darkness, Merecraft drifted off to sleep... <br>
<br>
_______________ <br>
<br>
He was back in the Tree. The poisoned blade was in his hand and he was striking out. Tunare watched him calmly as the blade plunged towards her heart. The goddess raised her hand and there was a flash of light. <br>
<br>
He was back in the Tree. The poisoned blade was in his hand and he was striking out. Tunare watched him calmly as the blade plunged towards her heart. The goddess raised her hand and there was a flash of light. <br>
<br>
He was back in the Tree. No, no... still the nightmare continued. Merecraft rolled uneasily as the dreams he had suffered ever since that fateful day played out in his feverish mind. The only times he had not dreamed of the night he had tried to kill his goddess was when Kassy was at his side. The half-elf moaned as the dream continued. <br>
<br>
He was back in the Tree. The poisoned blade was in his hand and he was striking out. Tunare watched him calmly as the blade plunged towards her heart. The goddess spoke. No, she didn't speak. This wasn't how it had happened, she had said nothing. She had simply raised her hand and banished him from her prescence. The goddess spoke. Her lips did not move, there was no need. Her voice simply echoed in the druids mind. <br>
<br>
&quot;Merecraft. My daughter is in grave danger. Go to her. Let your love guide you before it is too late.&quot; <br>
<br>
He was back in the Tree. The poisoned blade was in the Dark Elf's hand and he was striking out. Merecraft watched him calmly as the blade was drawn across Kassy's throat. Kassy raised her hand, grasping at the assassin's amulet and there was a flash of light. <br>
<br>
_______________ <br>
<br>
Merecraft awoke from the dream, his heart pounding. He pushed his greying hair back from his wet brow, gasping. He knew with a terrible, cold certainty that he had been given a message and that Kassy was in danger. Not stopping to wonder why Tunare would warn him of the attack the druid staggered to his feet. Still gasping he began to intone the prayer that would take him to the ancient stone circle in the plains of Karana. He did not know what he was doing, only that if he did not reach his love in time something terrible would befall her. <br>
<br>
Bubbles of magic rose up around him and he sank to his knees as a cold fear gripped his heart. His vision blurred a moment from tears, then the mountains faded from view. A second later the plains stretched out before the druid. <br>
<br>
He felt sick, and not just from the strange green mist that surrounded the druid ring here. This wasnt right. He needed to move quickly. His hands wove an intricate pattern in the air, his lips mumbling holy words. Merecraft felt his senses heighten as the magic infused his body. His heart began to beat faster, his arms and legs were twitching as energy coursed through them, and a second later he was away, running West, the Spirit of the Cheetah infusing his soul with speed. <br>
<br>
It was going to be the longest run of his life. He continued to pray to the Mother as he ran. He prayed that he would be in time. <br>
<br>
_______________ <br>
<br>
The half-elf ran through the narrow streets of Qeynos at breakneck speed. Merchants and citizens dodged out of the way, shouting after him to slow down. As he approached the docks area Merecraft slowed down slightly, the fear of what he would find when he reached Kassy's house slowing his approach. Grimly the druid gripped his claws and turned the corner to the home of his love. He stopped dead in his tracks as he saw the ornate wooden door to the enchantress's house swinging wildly on the hinges. <br>
<br>
Merecraft pushed the door open with his claws. The first thing he saw was the shattered plant pot near the doorway. Then his eyes adjusted to the dim light of the room, his infravision picking up the red form of a body sprawled on the desk. The body was fading from orange to a cool blue in his infravision as the heat left it. The only part remaining warm was a growing pool of blood. <br>
<br>
He froze for an instant, then he recognised it was his love pinned to the table. The small room smelt like an abbatoir. <br>
<br>
The world exploded. <br>
<br>
Screaming, the half-elf ran across the room, not wishing to believe what his eyes showed him. He spun, still screaming, tears streaming down his cheeks and strode to the table. A single sweep of his arm sent the various books, beakers, and papers flying into the air. His foot kicked out, the chair flying across the room to shatter on the far wall. He bent down, and gripped the table, forcing it over on its side causing glass and wood to break. <br>
<br>
&quot;NOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO&quot; <br>
<br>
He was too late. <br>
<br>
He spun again, his eyes rolling with madness. He gathered his prayers around him, his clawed fist bursting into flame, a rain of fire beginning to fall from the ceiling. Then the still cold form of Kassy moaned slightly... <br>
<br>
The druid stopped dead, the anger and madness flowing out of him in an instant. He dropped to his knees next to the fallen figure. There was blood everywhere. Then she moaned again, softly... &quot;Mother.... Mere...&quot; <br>
<br>
Merecraft forced his racing heart to calm down. Slowly he began to pray again, making sure that each word was intonated correctly, not daring to make even one mistake. If the magic fizzled now his love would be lost to him. As he prayed he moved his hands slowly over Kassy's broken form, the magic chlorophyll began to flow down, finding its way to the terrible wound in her blooded chest. The half-elf kept this up as long as he could, until finally all his magic was exhausted. He sat there holding Kassy's hand, sobbing softly to himself. Someone was going to pay for this. <br>
<br>
It may have been a few moments, it may have been an hour, Merecraft could not tell, when Kassy began to stir. Her eyes opened and slowly, painfully she began to sob. Merecraft gathered her in his arms, holding her tightly and thanking the Mother for the magic which had saved his love. Kissing her soft silver hair he hugged her to his chest, whispering to her. <br>
<br>
&quot;You are safe now love. I am here.&quot; <br>
<br>
Beneath the comforting words the druids thoughts were a boiling, seething fury. He would track down whoever had done this and make them suffer. He felt something he had not felt for many years. He felt hate. <br>
