Minz faded from view; the world darkened and went black, only to reappear in shades of shifting gray a moment later. Kassy lay on her back, just as she had fallen. The cut left by the assasin's blade had nearly stopped bleeding, the flow slowing to a trickle. There was, the elf knew in the back of her mind, not much left to bleed out. <br>
<br>
Tears were falling unchecked down her ebon cheeks, though not from the pain of the wound. That had nearly vanished, washed away by the pain of betrayal she felt. &quot;Mother, just let me die,&quot; she whispered, her voice soft and broken, &quot;Please...&quot; <br>
<br>
Her quiet plea was answered by voices in the mists. Appearing from the unending gray came a Fier'Dal man dressed in leather and green chainmail decorated with the wolfprint over a leaf symbol of his house. A small elven child was at his side, her brown eyes shining with the innocence and curiosity of youth. &quot;What left this one, honey?&quot; asked the ranger. <br>
<br>
&quot;Its a wolf pawprint, Papa,&quot; she answered in a melodic voice. <br>
<br>
&quot;Thats right, Kassy. Youre learning very fast!&quot; Starren Cal'saith smiled proudly down at his 4-year-old daughter. &quot;Lets go find your mother and tell her how well youre doing.&quot; <br>
<br>
Starren lifted the child into his arms and vanished back into the mists. <br>
<br>
Kassy forced herself up to a sitting position, staring after the elf who had just walked away. <br>
<br>
&quot;Papa!&quot; she cried as loudly as she could in her broken voice, &quot;Papa, wait! Dont leave me again...&quot; But he was gone. <br>
<br>
More footsteps echoed quietly from the shifting gray to her left and Kassy turned to face the new arrival. It was a young wood elven woman, perhaps 17 years of age. Her long brown hair was pushed back behind gracefully pointed years and large brown eyes looked out from beneath thick lashes. The girl was beautiful, even by elven standards, but there was a sadness about her that dulled the beauty ever so slightly. <br>
<br>
The ethreal elf maid walked through the Tier'dal as though she wasnt there. Kassy watched the younger version of herself as she walked through the dark tunnel that led to Surefall Glade. She watched as she came to the entrance of the sacred Glade, and she watched as she turned away, unable to enter and face what lay within. The girl vanished into the mists. <br>
<br>
An elven scream pierced the air, and Kassy turned to see herself locked within a spell of holding, her flawless tanned skin turning blue-black at the touch of Innoruuk's curse. She watched as the younger version of herself lost consiousness and as the Prince of Hate stood over her, laughing as he sent her back to Norrath. She watched as she awoke in Neriak, weak, lost, and dark elven. <br>
<br>
&quot;I dont want to see anymore,&quot; she said in a harsh whisper. The words caused the wound on her chest to bleed freely again. &quot;Mother, please... Let me have peace. Just let it all end...&quot; <br>
<br>
The image shifted and she was running in the pouring rain through the muddy streets of northern Freeport. She slipped and fell to her knees, her eyes falling to her reflection in the puddle before her. She slammed her fist into the water, shattering the image of the dark elf, &quot;No!&quot; she shouted into the stormy night, &quot;This isnt me. Im not Tier'dal! Im not...&quot; <br>
<br>
The puddle rippled and reformed. There was a second face in it staring back at her now. A hand came to rest on the apparition of Kassy's shoulder. &quot;Who are you? Your voice is that of an elf who once called to me for aid but your face is that of one of Innoruuk?s children. Tell me your name, and why you were at our guild hall this night.&quot; <br>
<br>
The young elf stuttered, looking up at the half-elf, &quot;Sir Merecraft...&quot; Her words were cut off as the pair vanished into the mist. <br>
<br>
Kassy turned her face away from where the image of her love had stood, her eyes filling with tears. A voice in the gray called her name. <br>
<br>
&quot;Kassy. C'mon, baby, its time to come home.&quot; The voice was soft, musical. <br>
<br>
&quot;Mamma?&quot; Kassy whispered as she rose slowly to her feet. &quot;Mamma, is it really you...?&quot; <br>
<br>
The mists swirled and shifted, taking the shape of the mother that Kassy could barely remember. The druidess stood in the mist, arms outstreached. She was tall for a wood elf, with hair that shone like fresh honey, natural copper highlights bringing out the emerald green of her eyes. Kassy began to walk slowly toward her, bringing a tanned hand to her face to wisk the dark hair from her eyes. The dark hair... <br>
<br>
Kassy looked down at herself. She was wearing her old druid's garb over her lightly tanned skin. She gasped, then closed her eyes, searching her mind for the words of magic that would mesmerize a foe or send send their mind screaming in anarchy. They were gone, replaced by the healing words of Tunare, prayers that would transport her across the world or infuse her with the spirit of the wolf. She opened her eyes and looked back. <br>
<br>
Laying upon the ground was the body of a young dark elf, the gaping wound upon her chest bleeding slowly as the last traces of life were leaving her body. Kassy looked at her a moment, then turned and walk away toward the voice from her past. She stopped as a second voice came from behind her, where the dark elf lay. <br>
<br>
&quot;Noooooo!&quot; <br>
<br>
The mists around the dying Tier'dal shifted, taking on the features of Kassy's home. Standing over the body of the dark elf was a half-elf dressed all in black. <br>
<br>
&quot;Mere...&quot; whispered the Fier'dal Kassy. <br>
<br>
He was storming through the room, tearing it apart in madness. As he looked at his fallen love again his fist began to glow, fire slowly starting to rain down from the celing. Kassy's heart broke as she watched him. She loved the druid with all her heart and she knew he felt the same for her. How could she leave him behind? <br>
<br>
She looked from Merecraft to the mother she had missed so dearly since she was a child. She looked also at looked at herself, at her tanned skin and dark hair. <br>
<br>
&quot;Kassy,&quot; Kirri's voice was soft, <br>
pleading. &quot;If you go back, if you accept the Tier'Dal body, you will never again wear your true form. We will never be together again. You can feel it in your heart... Please, baby, let it go. Tunare has given you this chance to come home.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I cant, Momma... I love him.&quot; <br>
<br>
A tear welled up in her shining brown eyes as she turned away from Kirri Cal'saith and stepped over to the fallen Tier'dal. She leaned down and touched the dark elf with tanned fingertips... <br>
<br>
Kassy's still, cold form moaned slightly... <br>
<br>
Merecraft stopped dead, the madness leaving him in an instant. He dropped to his knees next to the fallen figure. There was blood everywhere, the wound again trickling silently. Then she moaned again, softly... &quot;Mother... Mere...&quot; <br>
<br>
Merecraft forced his racing heart to calm down. Slowly he began to pray again, making sure that each word was intonated correctly, not daring to make even one mistake. If the magic fizzled now his love would be lost to him. As he prayed he moved his hands slowly over Kassy's broken form, the magic chlorophyll began to flow down, finding its way to the terrible wound upon her chest. The half-elf kept this up as long as he could, until finally all his magic was exhausted. He sat there holding Kassy's hand, sobbing softly to himself. <br>
<br>
Some time later Kassy stired. Her blue eyes opened and slowly, painfully she began to cry. Merecraft gathered her in his arms, holding her tightly and thanking Tunare for the magic which had saved his love. Kissing her soft silver hair he hugged her to his chest, whispering to her. <br>
<br>
&quot;You are safe now love. I am here.&quot; <br>
<br>
