<br>
Xareth was seated on the ground, absently poking a mostly dead campfire. The redish hues of the sunset stretched across the Karanas and bathed everything it touched with it's glow. An elephant calf lumbered along the ridge toward the water, flopping it's ears about absently. One could almost forget the plague that had cursed the land. The warrior added wood to the fire and ushered the flames back to life. His water supply was all but gone, and the water in the area was no longer safe to drink. He would have to boil it first. <br>
<br>
A lone tree stood near the once clean stream, stubbornly refusing to yield to the slow death of the plague. Skeletal branches sported a few withered leaves that fluttered aimlessly in the breeze. The thing reminded him of his own predicament, of his constant mental battle against the sickness that threatened to kill him. &quot;Soon,&quot; he muttered. Hopefully soon all of this would be over. A light sound caught the Dark Elf's attention, and he turned toward it, resting one hand on the hilt of a blade. <br>
<br>
The sound came again, a soft rustle. Something was off in the high grass. For a moment the Teir'Dal though it might be the calf, but dismissed the idea upon seeing it farther downstream. There were still many creatures roaming the savanna, but not all were friendly. He gently pulled a sword from it's sheath and approached the grass. Whatever was there was coming faster now, and making no attempt to hide itself. A dark form burst into view and nearly bowled over the warrior. <br>
<br>
An off balance warrior is always an easy target, and a Teir'Dal is no exception. The form came at him in a frenzy, and Xareth swung his blade about to parry, then danced away to face -- <br>
<br>
Minz?? <br>
<br>
He stood staring, not beleiving his eyes. Minz was crouched several feet away, his blade and clothing spotted with blood and earth, and looking for all the world like a caged animal. A once smiling face was now hollow, and the half elf's eyes reflected inner torment. Xareth kept his stance, unsure of the rogue's intent. &quot;What are you doing here?&quot; <br>
<br>
He'd spoken more harshly than intended, and the rogue's blind eyes narrowed in recognition. &quot;You,&quot; he growled. &quot;What have you done?!&quot; He moved slowly in a crouch, one hand testing the ground for footing, his face fixed in the Teir'Dal's direction. <br>
<br>
The sight of the half elf intrigued Xareth. He remembered one of his spies reporting the change that had taken place in the rogue. The spy spoke of the rogue's being in Paineel, and the amulet that had been bestowed upon him at the Teir'Dal's own cost. There seemed to be more blood collected on the rogue's chest. He wondered what that meant. <br>
<br>
&quot;Well,&quot; he said. &quot;You look the worse for wear, lost rogue. Again, what brings you to my camp?&quot; <br>
<br>
Minz rose, seeming to teeter on his balance for a moment. &quot;Worse for wear? You contracted me to slay one of my best friends, you bastard!&quot; He clenched his fists in rage, one hand gripping his dagger until the knuckles turned white. &quot;How DARE you do that to me?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, does that bother you? I see the gift that was given to you still hasn't taken it's full effect. And remember, you agreed to carry out a contract for me, on a target of my choosing. Na'Verdis has been a pain in my side for some time.&quot; Minz still stood clenching his fists, so Xareth sheathed his sword. there would be no fighting this time. &quot;Come now, tell me. Have you carried out your mission?&quot; <br>
<br>
The rogue didn't answer, but his lowered head and tear-stained face gave the warrior all the answer he needed. His messenger had hinted as much earlier that day. Still, Minz could not have picked a worse time to carry out the contract. Kassy was the only one who could sucessfully translate the language in his old diary, and if she failed, he was doomed. Minz had been forced to choose between friends, and in choosing Silverstarr over Kassy, he may very well have forfeited both of their lives, and his own as well. Xareth was furious that his order to back off the hunt until the translation was complete, but nothing could be done about it. All he could do was hope that the messenger returned with enough of a translation to figure out what was needed to lift the sickness. <br>
<br>
Xareth smiled, considering Minz's predicament. That amulet would slowly turn him into a Tier'Dal, mind, body, and soul. How many times had he used it? The possibilities opened up before him. Minz was the current leader of the Order of Elder Dragons. Those lightborn fools would follow him to the nine hells and back if he simply asked him to. If the amulet finished it's job, then his own wish to turn the Dragons to darkness could easily be completed. <br>
<br>
&quot;I hate you,&quot; Minz muttered, his voice dripping with venom. &quot;I hate you! My family, my friends, my life! All of it was taken because of you!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Really, Minz, you should see the positive side of things. Do you really wish to live out your existence leading some meager band of lightdwellers? Your amulet can give you many things. It will change who you are, and make you something much better.&quot; He moved toward the rogue, coming to stand right in front of him. Minz looked uneasy, but refused to budge. &quot;You can become one of my people, and live for a reason. The death of Kassy was simply the beginning, one of the trials you must face. Think about it for a moment. You have nothing left; you just said it yourself. You can begin a new life, and live well.&quot; <br>
<br>
Minz roared and launched at Xareth. The warrior saw it coming, but was too close to dodge, and fought desparately for footing as Minz tried to get a death lock on his throat. The rogue's blade came up to strike, and Xareth finally lost all balance. Both combatants fell heavily to the ground. <br>
<br>
Xareth twisted out from under the enraged rogue and managed to deflect the weapon with a bracer. It bit harshly into the metal armor, denting it badly and cutting into the Dark Elf's ruining flesh. The two grappled on the ground for a moment, rolling and kicking like pumas in the dust. Minz was in an asolute frenzy, shouting incoherently and slashing wildly with his dagger, and it was all Xareth could do to keep from getting badly injured. One slice caught him across the cheek, tearing into the half dark skin viciously. He managed to grab the half elf's swinging arm, and stop the blade attack. Then he punched him smartly in the face, dazing him. <br>
<br>
Xareth snatched the rogue's dagger and leapt to his feet, planting on boot firmly on the elf's chest. Minz was shaking his head, trying to clear it. He glared down at him coldly. &quot;What do you think you're doing?&quot; <br>
<br>
The rogue spat up at him, still furious. He tried squirming out from under the warrior's metal boot, so Xareth drew a sword with his free hand and levelled it's point at the rogue's face. Minz caught the sound of the blade and stopped instantly, feeling the prick of the sword's tip. <br>
<br>
Minz glared up at the warrior, his empty eyes seeming to find the dark face. &quot;Kill me already. I have nothing left to live for. You made certain of that!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;And why should I kill you,&quot; he retorted evenly, &quot;when you still have your uses? You are not as hopeless as you believe yourself, Pendragon.&quot; He smiled at the rogue's shocked reaction to the title. &quot;Aye, you still have your uses.&quot; He dropped the rogue's weapon next to it's owner and stepped away. Minz got up slowly, covered with dust, and found the fallen weapon after a bit of sweeping for it with a hand. <br>
<br>
&quot;Now,&quot; said Xareth. &quot;Get gone from here. I have other business to complete. I'll come find you when I am ready.&quot; He started to turn away, then thought better of it. &quot;I suggest you do not try anything foolish, Minz. You have completed your job, let it go at that.&quot; He watched Minz for a moment. It was apparent that the other was broken, feeling utterly lost and useless to anyone. Assassins were generally the type to keep from having close relationships with anyone, and preferred to keep to their own. This one, however, had taken leadership of a guild, and had even had a family. Losing the family had cost him dearly, and when his guild discovered that he was the instrument of Kassy's death, they might very well throw him to the wolves. <br>
<br>
But all of that was meaningless to the warrior. Minz was falling from his pedastal, turning and slowly shaping into something more useful. If the amulet finished it's job, soon Minz would no longer care, and might even gladly accept servitude to the Father's will. He was going to be patient. <br>
<br>
Xareth waited to see what Minz would do. <br>
